DBS Group Holdings 1Q 2024 financial results May 2, 2024

Strong start to the year
Record 1Q performance
o Total income and net profit reach new highs, ROE at record 19.4%
Loan growth better than recent quarters
o Loans increase 1% qoq, driven by a broad-based 3% rise in non-trade corporate loans
Group NIM stable, underlying trends in line with guidance
• o Commercial book NIM up 2bp qoq despite lower Hibor due to fixed-rate asset repricing; Casa outflows slow from the previous year
• o Markets Trading's deployment in high-quality assets accretive to net interest income but dilutive to NIM

<content-ref src='/page/2/SectionHeader/0'></content-ref><content-ref src='/page/2/ListGroup/65'></content-ref><content-ref src='/page/2/Picture/10'></content-ref><content-ref src='/page/2/PageFooter/11'></content-ref>
Strong start to the year

• Net fee income crosses $1bn for the first time
    • o Wealth management fees rise from stronger market sentiment and an expanded AUM base, card fees from higher spending
    • o Both increases additionally boosted by base effects, including Citi Taiwan consolidation
• Treasury customer sales reach new high

• Cost-income ratio at 37%
    • o Expense growth well managed, up 5% yoy ex-Citi Taiwan

• Asset quality resilient
    • o NPL ratio unchanged at 1.1%, SP remains low at 10bp of loans
• 1Q dividend of 54 cents on enlarged share base

<content-ref src='/page/3/SectionHeader/0'></content-ref><content-ref src='/page/3/SectionHeader/1'></content-ref><content-ref src='/page/3/ListGroup/150'></content-ref><content-ref src='/page/3/SectionHeader/6'></content-ref><content-ref src='/page/3/ListGroup/151'></content-ref><content-ref src='/page/3/Picture/11'></content-ref><content-ref src='/page/3/PageFooter/12'></content-ref>
Notwithstanding MAS decision not to extend 6-month pause on non-essential activities, will continue to focus on technology resiliency
Progress made in executing on technology resiliency roadmap, enabling:
• o Greater service availability
• o Alternate channels for payments and account enquiries should issues occur
• o Faster full recovery of services
• o Greater payments/ transaction certainty for payer and recipient
Several areas remain a work-in-progress
• o Continued simplification and strengthening of systems architecture
• o Building deeper expertise in centres of excellence for critical third-party technologies
• o Broadening use of artificial intelligence to further strengthen change management
• o Creating more monitoring tools so as to be able to detect potential issues more quickly

<content-ref src='/page/4/SectionHeader/0'></content-ref><content-ref src='/page/4/ListGroup/49'></content-ref><content-ref src='/page/4/Picture/9'></content-ref><content-ref src='/page/4/PageFooter/10'></content-ref>
Outlook
• Geopolitical risks persist, but macroeconomic conditions remain resilient
• Group net interest income to be modestly better than 2023 levels

• Commercial book non-interest income growth to be in mid-to-high teens percent
    • o Better-than-expected momentum in wealth management and treasury customer sales
• Total income growth to be 1-2% points above previous guidance of mid-single-digit
• Cost-income ratio to be in low-40% range
• SP assumed to normalise to 17-20bp although not seeing stress so far
• Net profit to be above 2023 levels
